---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
---
<Base title="Sturminster Newton" description="Discover Sturminster Newton – a beautiful old market town in the heart of the Blackmore Vale, Dorset, steeped in history and Thomas Hardy connections.">

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">

    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-2">Sturminster Newton</h1>
    <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium mb-10">In the heart of the Blackmore Vale, Dorset</p>

    <!-- Hero image -->
    <img
      src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506905925346-21bda4d32df4?w=1200&q=80"
      alt="Dorset countryside"
      class="w-full h-72 object-cover rounded-2xl mb-10 shadow-md"
    />

    <!-- Intro -->
    <section class="prose prose-stone max-w-none mb-12">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Sturminster Newton is a picturesque old market town nestled in the Blackmore Vale in
        north Dorset, close to the River Stour. With its medieval bridge, historic mill, and
        thriving local community, it's one of the most charming towns in the county.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The town sits within an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty and is surrounded by
        quintessential rolling Dorset countryside — the very landscape that inspired the
        novels of Thomas Hardy.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Thomas Hardy connection -->
    <section class="bg-amber-100 border-l-4 border-amber-400 rounded-r-xl p-6 mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-3">A Thomas Hardy Connection</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">
        Thomas Hardy lived in Sturminster Newton from 1876 to 1878 with his wife Emma,
        renting a house called Riverside Villa from local poet and tailor <strong>Robert Young</strong>
        — after whom our café takes its inspiration. Hardy described this as "our happiest time."
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">
        It was here that Hardy began writing <em>The Return of the Native</em> and later
        drew on the landscape and characters of the Blackmore Vale for
        <em>Tess of the D'Urbervilles</em> — two of the greatest novels in the English language.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Things to see -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stone-800 mb-6">Things to See &amp; Do Nearby</h2>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        {[
          {
            title: 'Sturminster Newton Mill',
            desc: 'A beautifully restored 18th-century working watermill on the River Stour, open to visitors throughout the year.',
          },
          {
            title: 'The Medieval Bridge',
            desc: 'One of Dorset\'s finest medieval bridges, spanning the River Stour — a lovely spot for a stroll.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Blackmore Vale',
            desc: 'Miles of stunning walking and cycling routes through Hardy\'s "Vale of the Little Dairies."',
          },
          {
            title: 'Weekly Market',
            desc: 'Sturminster Newton holds a traditional Monday market — a great place to pick up local produce.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Dorset Countryside',
            desc: 'Explore the surrounding villages, ancient churches, and sweeping hilltop views across north Dorset.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Local Pubs & Shops',
            desc: 'The town has a thriving independent high street, pubs, and community events year-round.',
          },
        ].map(({ title, desc }) => (
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-1">{title}</h3>
            <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm leading-relaxed">{desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Call to action -->
    <div class="bg-stone-800 text-amber-50 rounded-2xl p-8 text-center">
      <p class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Visiting the area?</p>
      <p class="text-amber-100/80 mb-6">
        Make Poets Corner Café your base — a perfect stop for breakfast or lunch
        before exploring everything the Blackmore Vale has to offer.
      </p>
      <a href="/contact" class="inline-block bg-amber-400 text-stone-900 font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-lg hover:bg-amber-300 transition-colors">
        Find Us
      </a>
    </div>

  </div>

</Base>
